        <div style="margin-top: 50px;">
            <h3 style="margin-bottom: 0;">Demographics</h3>
            <p>According to the Census of Canada Snapshot of 2016, 13,475 families lived in Beltline that same year. Of the 13,466 individuals living in the community, 88% were between 15 and 64 years. About 6% of the population were between 65 and 84 years old, and 4% were between 0 and 14 years old. A whopping 65% of houses in the area are rented out, while their owners occupy the rest. </p>
        </div>
        <div style="margin-top: 50px;">
            <h3 style="margin-bottom: 0;">Housing</h3>
            <p>Almost all of Beltline is made up of apartments. A little over 80% of the apartments are five storeys or more. There are about 200 row houses in the neighbourhood as well. Most of the Beltline dwellings were built after 1961, although you will find some dating back before 1960.</p>
        </div>
        <div style="margin-top: 50px;">
            <h3 style="margin-bottom: 0;">Developer/builder/history</h3>
            <p>The name Beltline originated from the city's municipal railway route No. 5 – the belt line. The early 20th century No. 5 trolley circled what is today's neighbourhood of Beltline.</p>
            <p>Despite the redevelopment and modernization of the neighbourhood, Beltline has strong ties with its past. Several buildings throughout its 12-decade history, including churches, warehouses, private homes, rooming houses, and schools, still stand today.</p>
        </div>
